observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:
(a)	Inventory Committee 
(i)	conduct a complete actual physical inventory count of all the PPEs owned by the Municipality pursuant to COA Circular 2020-006; (ii) exert more effort in securing the needed documents or information in the recognition and valuation of the donated PPEs presented above, otherwise record the same in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006; and (iii) coordinate with the Accounting Department the reconciliation of accounting records with the Report on the Physical Count of PPE for identification of differences in the PPE;
(b)	Municipal Treasurer, together with the Municipal Assessor, facilitate the titling of the 24 parcels of land already located and exert extra effort in locating the remaining 78 parcels owned by the Municipality;
(c)	OIC-Municipal Accountant 
(i)	compute and provide depreciation for the Road Networks asset account; and 
(ii)	make necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the PPE accounts; 
(d)	OIC-Municipal Accountant, together with the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Treasurer, initiate the proper recognition and inventory of the Local Road Network System as well as the drafting of the Local Road Network Map of the Municipality; and
(e)	Local Chief Executive instruct all department heads account for all donated PPEs under their custody and submit to the Accounting Department all documents pertaining thereto for proper recognition in the books.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, as Chairman of the Municipal Development Council (MDC), instruct the members and secretariat of the MDC and implementing departments to ensure 
(a) that development projects to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement and implementation ready; 
(b) timely completion and full implementation of the projects, at the same time, optimize the use of the fund to guarantee timely enjoyment of the benefits that the projects may provide to the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Human Resource Management Officer to:
(a)	continue to conduct a thorough review of its existing organizational structure in order to properly identify and establish its appropriate human resource complement and creation of additional permanent position which may be considered for regular functions of the agency;
(b)	hire job order personnel based on necessity and perform periodic performance evaluation and assessment of Job Order personnel to ensure value for money and avoid wastage of government funds by paying compensation to JOs who do not actually provide service, or whose services rendered do not commensurate to their compensation;
(c)	require JO personnel to properly accomplish their DTRs to reflect the actual number of days and time rendered and submit actual and quantified accomplishment reports to support payment of wages;
(d)	submit a written explanation on the noted differences and deficiencies on compensation/wages of JO personnel; 
(e)	refer to the provisions of CSC-DBM Circular No. 1, s. 2018, CSC-COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017, Section 2, Rule XI of the Revised Omnibus Rules on Appointments and Other Personnel Actions and CSC Memorandum Circular No. 24, series of 2002 regarding the policy guidelines on the hiring, supervision and payment of JO personnel.

observations.managementAction:
The Local Chief Executive informed that the following measures were undertaken to address the deficiencies in the hiring, payment and supervision of Job Order personnel:

Various planning such as Executive Legislative Agenda, Capacity Development and Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP) was conducted to establish the appropriate human resource complement and the creation of additional permanent positions of this Agency;

Memorandum was issued to require all JO personnel to properly accomplish their DTRs and accomplishment reports in order to properly support the payment of their wages;

The Human Resource Management Officer conducted investigation on the deficiencies/discrepancies on the wages of JO personnel. It was revealed that the incorrect salary disclosed by some personnel due to nervousness and lack of awareness on the Contract of Service hence, all department heads were reminded to explain to their staff the daily wage indicated in their contracts. It was also noted that for the 20 JO personnel the difference was due to typographical error and adjustments in their salary after considering their workload; and 

Department heads were reminded on the policy guidelines of CSC, DBM and COA on hiring, supervision of JO personnel and payment of their salaries and wages.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management hire job order personnel based on necessity and perform periodic performance evaluation and assessment thereon to ensure value for money and avoid wastage of government funds through payment of compensation to JOs who do not actually provide service, or whose services rendered do not commensurate to their compensation.

Further, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive, instruct the Human Resource Management Officer to:
initiate the conduct of the review of its existing organizational structure in order to properly identify and establish the Municipality’s appropriate human resource complement and create additional permanent position which may be considered for regular functions of the agency;
require JO personnel to properly accomplish their DTRs to reflect the actual number of days and time rendered and submit quantified accomplishment reports to support payment of wages;
refer to the provisions of Section 2, Rule XI of the Revised Omnibus Rules on Appointments and Other Personnel Actions and CSC Memorandum Circular No. 24, series of 2002 regarding the policy guidelines on the hiring, supervision, and payment of JO personnel.

